{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"117813e2-9c6c-4300-bcde-d559a2fe1508","content":"This is a TUnit project which uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively. TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` with a path pattern of `/assembly/namespace/class/test`. The command is:\n\n```\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args. The wildcards match any assembly/namespace, then filter to the `SmsNotificationTests` class and all its tests (`SendSms_HealthCheck`, `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d12a69c8-409a-4438-b7da-c93cee5557bc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (v0.6.120). TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For MTP-based runners, the filter syntax is different from VSTest's `--filter`.\n\nTUnit uses its own `--treenode-filter` for filtering. To filter by class name, the syntax is:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter pattern for TUnit is: `/assembly/namespace/class/test`\n\nSince TUnit uses `OutputType Exe`, you run it with `dotnet run`, not `dotnet test`. \n\nThough actually, TUnit can also work with `dotnet test` depending on the setup. With `dotnet test` and MTP in .NET 9+, you might use the standard filter syntax like `--filter \"ClassName=SmsNotificationTests\"` or pass the treenode filter through the command line arguments.\n\nThe treenode path structure follows `/assembly/namespace/class/test`, so filtering by class would look like `--treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"`. Let me figure out the most straightforward approach for the user.","outputTokens":626,"requestId":"6801:1E60:9CBCF2:B64413:69FD3DFF"},"id":"05136eb8-1e41-4556-a5cb-d8ebfb9d9023","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:36:13.868Z","parentId":"6244773e-bd78-4ac6-b117-340c2a75fffa"}
